These examples illustrate the strict nesting of metadata under the
\texttt{tags} object and telemetry under the \texttt{fields} object. By
grouping and pre-processing these payloads at the network edge, the CDM
successfully hides the underlying complexity of the multi-vector energy
system, ensuring the digital twin of the Learning Factory remains
synchronized.

\section{Validation}\label{sec-validation}

\subsection{Experimental Setup and
Conditions}\label{sec-experimental-setup}

In this section, the rigorous environment built to stress-test the
MING+React architecture is defined. A high-fidelity stochastic
simulation was orchestrated in Node-RED to model physical assets like
photovoltaic systems and wind turbines, employing open-source ingestion
tools similar to those described in modern energy monitoring literature
\citep{dani2025aipowered}. To validate the pipeline under realistic
conditions, we developed a custom simulation model utilizing a strict
corridor algorithm to mimic physical inertia and sensor noise. This
custom model provides a baseline for evaluating edge-level filtering
strategies similar to the fog-based sensor-ranking paradigms discussed
generally in \citep{costa2022focuser}. Unlike standard random number
generation, the algorithm operates on a recursive random walk where each
data point is constrained to a ±2\% window relative to its predecessor.
Mathematically, the next telemetry state \(x_t\) is computed recursively
as:

\[x_t = \max\left(x_{\min}, \, \min\left(x_{\max}, \, x_{t-1} + r_t \cdot (0.02 \cdot x_{t-1})\right)\right)\]

where \(r_t \sim \mathcal{U}(-1, 1)\) is a uniform random variable, and
\([x_{\min}, x_{\max}]\) represent physically realistic saturation
boundaries to prevent infinite drift. The ±2\% step size models the
physical thermal and mechanical inertia of cyber-physical assets (such
as photobioreactors and dyno engine benches) relative to the sampling
interval. A larger threshold would introduce unrealistic sensor jitter
that exceeds physical actuator slew rates, while a smaller step fails to
test the pipeline's dynamic rendering.

In the Node-RED middleware simulation nodes, this algorithm is
implemented as shown in Listing~\ref{lst-corridor-code}:

\begin{codelisting}

\caption{\label{lst-corridor-code}Node-RED JavaScript implementation of
the Strict Corridor Algorithm.}

\centering{

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{// Retrieve previous state or initialize}
\KeywordTok{const}\NormalTok{ prevVal }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ context}\OperatorTok{.}\FunctionTok{get}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}prevVal\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{||}\NormalTok{ initVal}\OperatorTok{;}
\CommentTok{// Generate uniform step in [{-}1, 1)}
\KeywordTok{const}\NormalTok{ r }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ (}\BuiltInTok{Math}\OperatorTok{.}\FunctionTok{random}\NormalTok{() }\OperatorTok{{-}} \FloatTok{0.5}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{*} \DecValTok{2}\OperatorTok{;} 
\CommentTok{// Compute new value constrained to ±2\% of prevVal}
\KeywordTok{let}\NormalTok{ newVal }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ prevVal }\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{ (r }\OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{ (prevVal }\OperatorTok{*} \FloatTok{0.02}\NormalTok{))}\OperatorTok{;} 
\CommentTok{// Apply saturation boundaries to prevent infinite drift}
\NormalTok{newVal }\OperatorTok{=} \BuiltInTok{Math}\OperatorTok{.}\FunctionTok{max}\NormalTok{(minVal}\OperatorTok{,} \BuiltInTok{Math}\OperatorTok{.}\FunctionTok{min}\NormalTok{(maxVal}\OperatorTok{,}\NormalTok{ newVal))}\OperatorTok{;} 
\NormalTok{context}\OperatorTok{.}\FunctionTok{set}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}prevVal\textquotesingle{}}\OperatorTok{,}\NormalTok{ newVal)}\OperatorTok{;}
\ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ newVal}\OperatorTok{;}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

}

\end{codelisting}%

Representative simulation parameters include Engine Speed
(\(x_0 = 3000\text{ RPM}\), range \([1000, 4500]\)), pH (\(x_0 = 7.0\),
range \([6.0, 8.5]\)), Active Power (\(x_0 = 12.5\text{ kW}\), range
\([0, 16]\)), and Medium Temperature
(\(x_0 = 25.0\text{ }^\circ\text{C}\), range \([15, 35]\)).

The twelve core physical vectors, which consist of six fast vectors and
six slow vectors, were simultaneously stressed under peak
high-concurrency load conditions. The simulation consisted of 10
concurrent publishers (representing the 10 data categories active in the
Node-RED flow, matching the database schema measurements). Each
publisher transmitted telemetry messages at a uniform 3-second interval,
representing a sustained aggregate messaging rate of 3.33 messages per
second. The stability test run lasted continuously for a total duration
of 30 minutes, publishing a total packet count of 6,000 telemetry
messages (600 packets per category). Physical assets target distinct
rates, with 1 second for fast vectors and 5 seconds for slow vectors
(Table~\ref{tbl-vectors}). However, this uniform 3-second simulation
rate created a sustained, high-concurrency load on the middleware,
serving as a benchmark for reliability \citep{kaestner2018design}.

The telemetry dataset visualized in Figure~\ref{fig-corridor} was
extracted from the InfluxDB \texttt{renewable\_energy} bucket using the
\texttt{capture\_realtime.ps1} PowerShell script via the InfluxDB REST
API. The plot demonstrates the temporal continuity modeled by the
stochastic corridor algorithm. While the KIOZE specification defines
physics-based models for production hardware, this validation MVP uses
the stochastic corridor algorithm. This helps simulate physical inertia
and test persistence under continuous, noisy conditions.

\textbf{Use of generative AI.} During the preparation of this
manuscript, the authors used Anthropic Claude (Sonnet 4.x and Opus 4.x)
for source-bound section drafting, structural editing, figure-source
generation, and bibliography auditing, under the workflow documented in
the project repository. All technical claims about the KIOZE Edu-Bad
architecture were independently verified against the system
specification document. All citations were independently verified
against the cited sources. The authors reviewed and edited every AI
output and take full responsibility for the content of this publication.

\begin{figure}

\centering{

\pandocbounded{\includegraphics[keepaspectratio]{pics/Figure_3_Corridor_vs_Noise.pdf}}

}

\caption{\label{fig-corridor}Comparison of the strict corridor algorithm
against unfiltered white noise. The plot shows the normalized active
power (\(active\_power\_kw\)) vector over a 300-second simulation
window. The dataset was extracted from the InfluxDB
\texttt{renewable\_energy} bucket using the
\texttt{capture\_realtime.ps1} PowerShell script via the InfluxDB REST
API. The x-axis represents Elapsed Time in seconds (s), and the y-axis
represents the normalized power output (\%). The legend compares the
strict corridor simulation path (labeled ``Temporal Continuity'',
representing physical inertia) against the baseline random walk with
unfiltered noise (labeled ``Stochastic Volatility'', illustrating
unconstrained fluctuations).}

\end{figure}%

\subsection{Observations: The Pipeline in
Motion}\label{sec-observations}

This topology was designed to synchronize twelve distinct data vectors
that represent the intersection of high-frequency mechanical speed and
slow biological inertia. By resolving the challenges of disparate
ingestion frequencies, this normalization creates a ``universal
translator'' effect, ensuring that every data point adopts a unified,
synchronized JSON format regardless of its source frequency. Enforcing
this structural unity transforms the raw telemetry stream into a
high-integrity, homogenized dataset.

\subsection{Performance Results}\label{sec-results}

The architectural feasibility and data routing of the pipeline were
evaluated within a local, containerized development environment. This
setup served as a validation testbed to verify that the universal
translator and edge-level null-pruning logic operate correctly without
introducing significant computational overhead.

First, valid packet integrity was verified through a comparative audit
between the Node-RED ingress counts and InfluxDB point counts. Over a
sample of \(N = 1000\) valid telemetry packets, the audit verified zero
packet loss. This yields a packet integrity rate of 100\% with zero
statistical variance (\(\sigma^2 = 0\)). To evaluate the edge-level
null-pruning loop, we manually injected \(N = 50\) malformed packets
into the MQTT broker over a 10-minute trial. We define a malformed
packet as a JSON payload where one or more telemetry fields contain a
literal \texttt{null} value. The scoring rule defined accuracy as the
ratio of successfully pruned null fields to the total injected null
fields. The evaluation achieved 100\% null-pruning accuracy. Every null
key was successfully removed at the middleware layer. This prevented
empty values from leaking into InfluxDB, with zero database corruption
observed.

Second, API query response latency was benchmarked using the
\texttt{.NET} \texttt{System.Diagnostics.Stopwatch} utility. We recorded
\(N = 500\) HTTP GET requests to the
\texttt{/api/summary/engine\_test\_bench} endpoint via the Nginx proxy.
This test yielded an average (mean) response latency of
\(42.5\text{ ms}\) with a standard deviation of
\(\sigma = 3.8\text{ ms}\). The median response time was
\(42.1\text{ ms}\) and the 95th percentile (\(P_{95}\)) was
\(48.2\text{ ms}\). This is in contrast to heavy immersive 3D or
Augmented Reality (AR) digital twins that report latencies exceeding 100
ms \citep{caiza2023digitaltwin}. To measure the middleware's internal
transformation overhead, we used Node-RED timestamp hooks across
\(N = 1000\) processed packets. This recorded the duration between the
gateway's MQTT ingress and the database write input hook. The average
transformation overhead was \(0.85\text{ ms}\) with a standard deviation
of \(\sigma = 0.12\text{ ms}\) and a 95th percentile of
\(1.02\text{ ms}\). This confirms that the CDM normalization logic runs
in sub-millisecond times, causing negligible overhead on the edge node.

Finally, end-to-end system success was measured during a 30-minute
stability run under peak simulation load (totaling 6,000 published
telemetry packets). The pipeline achieved an end-to-end success rate of
99.8\% (5,988 out of 6,000 packets successfully written). The remaining
12 packets were dropped during transient client socket reconnects under
concurrency spikes. This yields a success rate variance of
\(\sigma^2 = 0.002\) over the test duration.

Table~\ref{tbl-metrics} summarizes the MING+React pipeline functional
verification metrics obtained in the simulation validation testbed. The
system was evaluated to confirm it meets the functional targets required
for learning factory simulation and visualization.

